{
    "analysis": "We computed global P95/P5 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) across the full metric.csv, filtered metrics to the incident window, and counted anomalies per (cmdb,kpi). Results show many constant KPIs (p95==p5) such as socket/diskio which should be ignored. Among candidate services, checkoutservice and currencyservice show meaningful high anomalies on CPU/latency/memory; emailservice shows many low-latency events (likely benign). We still need to (a) quantify severity and persistence of the high anomalies (consecutive anomalous minutes) to identify real faults, and (b) if multiple services are faulty, use traces/logs to find the most downstream faulty service in call chains. No trace/log analysis has been done yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the already-calculated global thresholds and the filtered metric-window data, find candidate faults by focusing only on (cmdb_id,kpi_name) where p95 != p5 and anomaly_count_high > 0. For each candidate (cmdb_id,kpi_name) produce a compact row with: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count_high, earliest_anomaly_utc, max_value_in_window, p95, severity_ratio = (max_value_in_window - p95)/p95. Also compute consecutive-high-anomaly-run statistics within the incident window: number_of_runs_with_length>=2, earliest_run_start_utc (for runs >=2), and max_run_length (minutes). Return a table limited to top 20 rows sorted by severity_ratio descending. Keep outputs compact and textual. If no candidates remain after excluding constant KPIs, say so."
}

