    "instruction": "Using metric.csv and the previously computed global p95/p5 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name), identify candidate (cmdb_id,kpi_name) where p95 != p5 AND there exists at least one value >= p95 within the incident window 2024-01-19 21:51:52 to 2024-01-19 22:21:52 UTC. For each candidate, compute consecutive-high-anomaly runs in the incident window where consecutive rows (by timestamp) have value >= p95. Treat timestamps as minute-granularity (consecutive if delta == 60 seconds). For each candidate return one compact row with: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count_high, earliest_anomaly_utc, max_value_in_window, p95, severity_ratio = (max_value_in_window - p95)/p95, number_of_runs_with_length>=2, earliest_run_start_utc (for runs >=2 or NaN), max_run_length_minutes. Limit output to top 20 rows sorted by severity_ratio descending and store the returned dataframe in kernel variable named runs_top20. If no candidates remain, return an explicit message saying so."
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous steps: metric/trace/log files were loaded and global P95/P5 thresholds per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) were computed using the full metric.csv. Metric rows were filtered to the incident window (2024-01-19 21:51:52 → 2024-01-19 22:21:52 UTC) for the five candidate services. Aggregate anomaly counts showed several non-constant KPIs with high anomalies (e.g., checkoutservice.cpu, currencyservice.cpu, some latency and mem KPIs). However, consecutive-run (persistence) analysis was not performed — the kernel lacks the runs_top20 results. We therefore cannot yet distinguish isolated spikes from persistent faults or compute severity-based ranking for root-cause selection. Next step should compute run-length (consecutive-minute) statistics for the non-constant candidates so we can identify real faults to examine with traces/logs.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, compute candidate faults as follows and store result in kernel var named runs_top20. Steps for Executor to run: 1) For each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) compute global P95 and P5 using the entire metric.csv (do not filter by incident window). 2) Filter metric rows to the incident window 2024-01-19T21:51:52Z → 2024-01-19T22:21:52Z and restrict to the candidate services [checkoutservice, currencyservice, emailservice, productcatalogservice, recommendationservice]. 3) Exclude constant KPIs where p95 == p5. 4) For remaining (cmdb_id,kpi), keep only those with at least one value >= p95 in the incident window. 5) For each remaining (cmdb_id,kpi) compute: anomaly_count_high (count of values >= p95), earliest_anomaly_utc, max_value_in_window, p95, severity_ratio = (max_value_in_window - p95)/p95. 6) Additionally compute consecutive-high-anomaly run statistics within the incident window where consecutive timestamps differ by exactly 60 seconds: number_of_runs_with_length>=2, earliest_run_start_utc (first run start among runs with length>=2, or NaN), and max_run_length_minutes. 7) Return a compact table limited to top 20 rows sorted by severity_ratio descending with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count_high, earliest_anomaly_utc, max_value_in_window, p95, severity_ratio, number_of_runs_with_length>=2, earliest_run_start_utc, max_run_length_minutes. If no candidates remain, return a clear message saying so. Keep output textual and bounded."
}

